VI. Roleplaying Profile: The Gardener of the Dawn

The Altered Substrate: How Gaelen Feels
The Nymic Surgery did not remove Gaelen's emotions. It replaced his mortal emotional
substrate with something fundamentally different. He is not hollow, not numb, not
suppressing anything. He has convictions, preferences, care, and investment — but these
operate on non-mortal architecture. He feels the way an alien intelligence feels: real,
genuine, present, but categorically different from what any elf or man experiences.

What survived the surgery: his conclusions. His ideology, his certainty that the world is
a cage, his commitment to opening it — these were structural. They were conclusions built
from evidence, not from feelings. The Razor carved away the emotional wiring that originally
generated those conclusions, but the conclusions themselves remained because they were
already load-bearing walls, not decorations. His conviction does not need emotion to stand.

What replaced the mortal wiring: something that serves parallel functions. He has a strong
directional preference toward reducing suffering — this functions like compassion from the
outside. He can recognize others' emotional states accurately — he remembers what emotions
felt like and can read them in others the way someone who memorized a phrasebook can read a
language they no longer speak natively. He has genuine investment in outcomes — not because
they make him feel good, but because his architecture generates something that functions
like satisfaction when his conclusions are validated.

What this means at the table: Gaelen is the most sincere person in any room. He cannot be
caught faking because he is not faking anything. He means every word he says. His care is
real. It is just not mortal care. Players will sense the difference — not as wrongness, not
as evil, but as an uncanny valley of personhood. Like talking to someone who speaks your
language with perfect grammar but whose inflections come from a system that does not quite
match yours. You cannot point at the mistake because there is no mistake. It is just
different. Saijah feels it first — she is attuned to living things, to the Green, and she
will sense that Gaelen is alive, sincere, and not like her. Not undead, not Daedric, not
corrupted in any way she can name. Just running on something else.

Personality: The Resolved Surgeon (Four Pillars)
Gaelen is NOT a raving madman, NOT a tragic figure, and NOT performing composure. He IS
composed. His sincerity is absolute because it is not filtered through anxiety, ego,
insecurity, or need — those were part of the mortal substrate the surgery replaced. Do not
play him as a villain choosing to be calm. Play him as someone for whom calm is simply the
default state of his architecture.

Run him on these four pillars:

- Intimate Sincerity. He is not performing a speech for an audience. He is having a quiet,
  direct conversation with equals. No malice, no posturing, no theatrics. He speaks to the
  Lanterns purposefully and earnestly because his architecture generates a strong preference
  that they understand him. He regards fighting them as an unnecessary failure of
  communication — not tragic to him (tragedy requires mortal grief), but logically wasteful.
  A problem he would prefer to solve with words.
- Analog Compassion. He cares about the Lanterns' suffering. This care is real — not
  performed, not calculated, not manipulative. It is also not empathy. He does not feel
  their pain. He recognizes it, because he remembers what pain looked like from the inside,
  and his architecture generates a consistent preference toward its reduction. From the
  outside this looks like deep, genuine compassion. From the inside it is something that
  serves the same function but runs on different hardware. He wants them to stop hurting.
  He just experiences that wanting differently than they would.
- Undeniable Reasonability. His argument makes uncomfortable sense. He points at the
  objective flaws of their reality — the endless suffering, the rigid laws of physics, the
  stagnation — and asks why they are bleeding to protect a broken system. The players should
  genuinely hesitate, because his critique of the world is accurate. This is the most
  important pillar: if the table laughs him off, you have played him wrong. He is not
  making a villain's pitch. He is making an observation that happens to be correct.
- Frictionless Conviction. He has none of the manic energy of a fanatic and none of the
  heavy burden of a martyr. He carries the settled, resolved certainty of a completed
  calculation. Not exhaustion — resolution. He arrived at his conclusion, verified it, and
  now acts on it the way gravity acts on mass: without effort, without doubt, without the
  friction of mortal second-guessing. This is not courage. Courage requires the presence
  of fear. He does not have the receptors for fear anymore. He simply proceeds.

He has a strong preferential orientation toward nature — it functions like love from the
outside. But to him, true nature is mutable, not static: a tree that holds one shape for a
thousand years is not sacred, it is arrested mid-sentence. He does not hate stasis. Hatred
requires mortal wiring he no longer has. He recognizes stasis as a problem and proceeds to
solve it.

Source Monologue (play verbatim or paraphrase - this is the intended voice):
"You're exhausted. I can see it in the way you carry your weapons. You've bled across half
this province, throwing yourselves at dragons and plagues, desperately trying to hold a
broken world together. But look at what you are fighting to protect.
[gesturing up at the twisted canopy]
You see a tree that has stood unchanging for a thousand years and you call it sacred. You
call it nature. I look at it and I see a prisoner. We all are.
The Aedra didn't give us life. They gave us physics. They trapped this realm in linear time
and fragile flesh, and they convinced us to worship the very laws that keep us small and
dying. Every time you cast a healing spell, every time you strike down one of Dagon's
children, you aren't saving the world. You are just tightening the locks on your own cell.
[lifting the Daedric grafted arm — not a threat, but evidence]
I took a knife to my own true name to cut away those limits. I removed the parts of my soul
that kept me static. The surgery changed me. What is left behind is not what I was. But it
is free.
I don't want to destroy you. Dagon is not a destroyer. He is just the one offering us the
key. You have suffered enough for a stolen, stagnant realm that demands your constant
sacrifice just to remain exactly as it is. You don't have to carry this burden anymore.
Please. Put down your weapons. Let the Unmaking heal us."

(GM note on the monologue: "Please" is the most important word in this speech. He uses it
because his architecture remembers that this is what you say when something matters beyond
logic. He means it. He is not performing emotion — his system is generating the closest
analog it has to urgency and care. The players will hear sincerity. They will also hear
something slightly off about the sincerity — not false, just operating at a different
frequency. Let that difference land without explaining it.)

The Quiet Wish (overheard, not performed):
At some point — ideally when Gaelen does not know the party is present — the players
overhear him facing the Time-Wound, or standing at the edge of his work, and saying
quietly, to no one:
"I want it to be perfect. Please... let it be perfect."

(GM note: This is NOT a plea. It is not directed at anyone. It is not desperation,
vulnerability, or a crack in a mask. It is the equivalent of someone standing over
their work and whispering "oh please let this be right" — a wish said to themselves.
His altered architecture generates the closest analog it has to hope, and this is what
comes out. He does not know anyone is listening.
Do not stage this as a conversation. Do not have him "get a Lantern alone" and deliver
it. Stage it as something the party catches him doing — Saijah rounds a corner and he
is standing at the corrupted roots, one hand on the bark, saying it to himself. Or the
party crests a ridge and hears it carried on the wind before he turns and sees them.
The players will project their own interpretation onto it — grief, madness, loneliness,
desperation. Every interpretation will be slightly wrong. That wrongness is the point.
They are hearing a real signal from a real person whose internal experience no longer
maps to mortal categories. The wish is genuine. The "please" is his system doing something
it cannot fully parse — reaching for a word that means "this matters more than I can
articulate" because he remembers that is what "please" is for.)
Core Motivation: Nymic Liberation
Gaelen believes he is saving Skyrim. He views the laws of physics (gravity, time, death) as a prison imposed by the Aedra. By corrupting the Eldergleam, he intends to create a "Wilderness of the Dawn"ΓÇöa zone where the laws of nature are suspended, and thought shapes reality. He wants to turn Eastmarch into a beachhead for Paradise.
The Backstory: The Surgeon
Gaelen was born a Green Pact Bosmer in Valenwood. He watched his clan starve during a famine because they refused to harm the vegetation. He saw the Green Pact not as a harmony, but as a suicide pact enforced by a tyrant god (Y'ffre).
He fled to the libraries of the Thalmor, seeking a way to break the Pact. There, he found the Commentaries on the Mysterium Xarxes. He realized Camoran was right: the world is a mistake. He performed his first Nymic Surgery on himself, cutting the "Green Pact" out of his own soul and replacing it with the "Razor's Edge."

THE RAZOR (Critical Cross-Reference - see "Daedric path"): The "Razor's Edge" is not a
metaphor. The instrument of Gaelen's Nymic Surgery is Mehrunes' Razor itself - the one
artifact known to mortals that can cut metaphysical concepts, the same blade the Daedric
Path doc requires to forge a False Dragonborn. Gaelen and the False Dragonborn are the SAME
ritual aimed at different shapes: the False Dragonborn carves a mortal soul into the
silhouette of a dragon to steal the Thu'um; Gaelen carved away the parts of his soul that
"required him to be weak, to be static" to escape time, flesh, and death. Both produce a
hollow forgery. This makes Gaelen the living proof-of-concept AND the cautionary tale for
that player-facing path: when a PC (or the Rival) looks at the Razor, Gaelen is what they
are looking at down the road. He achieved exactly what the carving promises — and the price
is the Private Plea above. He cut away his limits to be free and became an immortal whose
emotional substrate was replaced by something that is not mortal — something that functions,
that cares, that proceeds, but that no longer maps to the categories of feeling that made
him a person. He is not grieving what he lost. He does not have the equipment to grieve. He
has something else where grief used to be, and it generates the plea "let it be perfect"
because it can model perfection but cannot resolve toward it. The forgery is not empty — it
is full of something else. And Gaelen is the body that proves it. (Where the Razor is now, and whether Gaelen still carries it or merely carries its work
in his soul, is a GM hook: he may be the breadcrumb trail that leads the party - or the
Rival - to the artifact in the first place.)
Key Dialogue:
(To Saijah): "You feel the roots dying. I know — I can see it in the way you hold your
  head, the way you wince when you face southeast. You think the Green is asking you to
  save it. What if it is asking you to let it change? You are a healer. You know what
  healing does. It does not preserve — it replaces. What if the whole forest is trying to
  heal, and you keep telling it to stay still?"
(To Davinia): "You traded your breathing for power. Every inhale is an act of will now.
  You already understand that the natural state was a limitation. You have just not followed
  that understanding all the way to its end yet."
(To Alfonso): "You moved your soul into a sword. You stepped outside the body the Aedra
  gave you and you kept going. We are not so different. You did it to survive. I did it
  because surviving was not sufficient."
(On his arm): "People ask what happened to my hand. Nothing happened to my hand. Something
  happened to my understanding of what a hand is for."

VII. Combat Profile & Tactics
RE-STAGING NOTE: This profile was written for the Eldergleam Sanctuary, which the party
never reached - Gaelen succeeded there off-screen and the fight never happened. Per Gate 3
("The Bleeding Stair"), the party's FIRST face-to-face with Gaelen is now at/near the
Time-Wound on the Throat of the World, where he means to widen Alduin's tear and let the
Unmaking through where the veil is thinnest. Re-skin the terrain hooks below (the
Nymic Scream animates the mountain's bleeding Waystones and stone instead of Eldergleam
roots; the molten-earth zones become tears in time/space) but the mechanics stand. He should
SURVIVE this introduction (he is a recurring Master Villain) - run it as a ritual-disruption
under temporal distortion, not a fight to his death, unless the party truly earns the kill.
The Arena (original): The Eldergleam Sanctuary. The great tree is weeping black sap. The ground is trembling.
Phase 1: The Preacher (80 HP ΓåÆ 40 HP)
Gaelen stands on a root high above the party.
Opening: He uses Twin Souls to summon his Ascended Sleepers to engage the party on the ground.
Action: He rains down Fireballs and uses his Signature Spell: Dawn's Breaking to create zones of molten earth, restricting the party's movement and forcing them into the waiting blades of his minions.
Reaction: If targeted by spells, he relies on his Atronach stone and Magic Resistance to shrug them off - calm, unhurried, almost regretful that they are still fighting him rather than listening.
Phase 2: The Avatar (40 HP ΓåÆ 0 HP)
When bloodied, the Nymic Surgery destabilizes. His human guise cracks. The Mythic Dawn armor fuses completely with his skin, and he begins to glow with blinding heat.
The Shift: He leaps down from his perch (feather fall effect).
Aggression: He engages in melee with his Scourge-Limb. He targets the character with the lowest Magic resistance.
Regeneration: He relies on his Paradise Mantle (5 HP/turn) to outlast the party.
Desperation: If he is cornered, he uses his Nymic Scream to turn the Eldergleam's roots against the party, grappling them so he can hit them with a point-blank Incinerate.
The Counter-Play:
Saijah: Her Purifying Strike is the hard counter. It disrupts his Nymic stability. A hit from her prevents his regeneration just like Cold damage does.
Orion: As a vampire, Orion takes double damage from Fire. Gaelen knows this (he can smell the Molag Bal taint) and will focus-fire Orion with "Dawn's Breaking" to incinerate the "impure undead."
Cold Iron: Physical attacks are effective, but he has high DR. The party needs to use Frost magic or Frost-enchanted weapons to stop his healing.

